        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-04-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-04-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="276"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d276">
                <head>276. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_davis-jeanne-w">Jeanne
                        Davis</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the Chairman of
                    the National Security Council Interdepartmental Group for East Asia (<persName
                        corresp="#p_habib-philip-c">Habib</persName>), Washington, April 19,
                        1976.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d276fn1">Source: <persName
                            corresp="#p_ford-gerald-r">Ford</persName> Library, <gloss
                            target="#t_nsc">NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–36,
                            <gloss target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 226, Review of U.S. Policy Toward
                        the Korean Peninsula. Secret; <gloss target="#t_nodis">Nodis</gloss>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d276fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_davis-jeanne-w">Davis</persName> asked the <gloss
                            target="#t_nsc">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for East Asia to
                        resume work on <gloss target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 226.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1976-04-19">April 19, 1976</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>NATIONAL SECURITY COUNCIL<lb/>WASHINGTON D.C. 20506</p>
                <p>April 19, 1976</p>
                <p>MEMORANDUM FOR<lb/>The Chairman <lb/>
                    <gloss target="#t_nsc">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for East
                    Asia<lb/>Department of State</p>
                <p>SUBJECT: Review of U.S. Security Policy Toward the Korean Peninsula: <gloss
                        target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 226</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 226 of May 27, 1975 called for a review of
                    U.S. policy toward the Korean Peninsula. The <gloss target="#t_nssm"
                        >NSSM</gloss> response was delayed pending the broad review of U.S.
                    interests and security objectives in the Asia-Pacific area (<gloss
                        target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 235), which has now been completed.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_nsc">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for East Asia
                    should now resume work on <gloss target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> 226, focusing on
                    the question of the U.S. security role in the Republic of Korea over the next
                    three to five years. The review should concentrate on the following specific
                    issues: <list>
                        <item>— the level of U.S. military presence in Korea.</item>
                        <item>— the extent of military assistance to the <gloss target="#t_rok"
                                >ROK</gloss>.</item>
                        <item>— U.S. policy on <gloss target="#t_rok">ROK</gloss> military
                            self-sufficiency, including advanced weapons and technology
                            transfers.</item>
                        <item>— operational control of U.S., Korean and other <gloss target="#t_un"
                                >U.N.</gloss> forces to include alternatives to the present <gloss
                                target="#t_un">U.N.</gloss> Command structure.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_nssm">NSSM</gloss> response should be submitted to the
                    Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs no later than June
                    10.</p>
                <p>[signed] <lb/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_davis-jeanne-w">Jeanne W. Davis</persName>
                    <lb/> Staff Secretary</p>
            </div>
        </body>
